{
    "blocks": [
        {
            "id": "intro_sorting",
            "elements": [
                {
                    "type": "heading",
                    "content": "Sorting Lists",
                    "properties": {
                        "level": 1
                    }
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "Often you need to organize lists in a specific order. Python provides powerful methods to sort lists in ascending or descending order."
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "There are two ways to sort: modifying the original list or creating a new sorted copy."
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "id": "sort_method",
            "elements": [
                {
                    "type": "heading",
                    "content": "The sort() Method",
                    "properties": {
                        "level": 2
                    }
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "The `sort()` method sorts a list **in place**, meaning it modifies the original list directly."
                },
                {
                    "type": "code",
                    "content": "numbers = [5, 2, 8, 1, 9]\nnumbers.sort()\nprint(numbers)",
                    "properties": {
                        "language": "python",
                        "output": "[1, 2, 5, 8, 9]"
                    }
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "The list is now sorted from smallest to largest (ascending order)."
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "id": "sort_strings",
            "elements": [
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "You can also sort lists of strings. They get sorted alphabetically."
                },
                {
                    "type": "code",
                    "content": "fruits = [\"orange\", \"apple\", \"banana\"]\nfruits.sort()\nprint(fruits)",
                    "properties": {
                        "language": "python",
                        "output": "['apple', 'banana', 'orange']"
                    }
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "Strings are sorted in alphabetical order (A to Z)."
                }
            ]
        },
        {
